<body>
    <h1>Build - Inclure une ressource externe (INTERNET)</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <p>Cet article d=C3=A9crit comment acc=C3=A9der =C3=A0 une ressourc=
e INTERNET durant un build docker. Un cas d'usage est de r=C3=A9cup=C3=A9re=
r l'autorit=C3=A9 de certification Banque de France dont le point de public=
ation est sur INTERNET.</p>
<div class=3D"confluence-information-macro confluence-information-macro-inf=
ormation">
<p class=3D"title">Pr=C3=A9-requis</p>
<span class=3D"aui-icon aui-icon-small aui-iconfont-info confluence-informa=
tion-macro-icon"></span>
<div class=3D"confluence-information-macro-body">
<p>Le daemon docker sur lequel le build sera r=C3=A9alis=C3=A9 doit aussi u=
tiliser un proxy pour par exemple r=C3=A9aliser un pull d'une image sur doc=
ker hub. Cette configuration est normalement d=C3=A9j=C3=A0 r=C3=A9alis=C3=
=A9e mais si votre build =C3=A9choue sur votre premi=C3=A8re commande : FRO=
M jboss/keycloak:3.4.0.Final cela est probablement d=C3=BB =C3=A0 un probl=
=C3=A8me de configuration du proxy au niveau du daemon docker.</p>
</div>
</div>
<p>Afin de pouvoir utiliser des commandes qui doivent acc=C3=A9der =C3=A0 I=
NTERNET au sein de votre Dockerfile, vous devez positionner des variables d=
'environnement</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">=20
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: bash; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">ENV htt=
p_proxy "http://&lt;proxy.address&gt;:3128"
ENV https_proxy "http://&lt;proxy.address&gt;:3128"
ENV HTTP_PROXY "http://&lt;proxy.address&gt;:3128"
ENV HTTPS_PROXY "http://&lt;proxy.address&gt;:3128"

RUN curl -o /etc/pki/ca-trust/source/anchors/racine-1.2.250.1.115.200.2.3.1=
.1.1.pem http://ae.certificats.banque-france.org/igc-bdf-v2/cert/ac/racine-=
1.2.250.1.115.200.2.3.1.1.1.cer
RUN update-ca-trust</pre>=20
</div>
</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Dans cet exemple, il n'est pas n=C3=A9cessaire de positionner les variab=
les HTTPS puisqu'on fait juste une requ=C3=AAte HTTP. Mais cela servirait s=
'il y avait d'autres actions (type apt-get ou yum install, ou d'autres curl=
 ou wget sur INTERNET)</p>
<p>Article sur les variables =C3=A0 utiliser suivant les outils : <a href=
=3D"https://unix.stackexchange.com/questions/212894/whats-the-right-format-=
for-the-http-proxy-environment-variable-caps-or-no-ca" class=3D"external-li=
nk" rel=3D"nofollow">https://unix.stackexchange.com/questions/212894/whats-=
the-right-format-for-the-http-proxy-environment-variable-caps-or-no-ca</a><=
/p>
<div class=3D"confluence-information-macro confluence-information-macro-inf=
ormation">
<span class=3D"aui-icon aui-icon-small aui-iconfont-info confluence-informa=
tion-macro-icon"></span>
<div class=3D"confluence-information-macro-body">
<p>There is no central authority who assigns an official meaning to environ=
ment variables before applications can use them. <a href=3D"http://pubs.ope=
ngroup.org/onlinepubs/9699919799/basedefs/V1_chap08.html" class=3D"external=
-link" rel=3D"nofollow">POSIX</a> defines the meaning of some variables (<c=
ode>PATH</code>, <code>TERM</code>, =E2=80=A6) and lists several more in a =
non-normative way as being in common use, all of them in uppercase. <code>h=
ttp_proxy</code> and friends isn't one of them.</p>
<p>Unlike basically all conventional environment variables used by many app=
lications, <code>http_proxy</code>, <code>https_proxy</code>, <code>ftp_pro=
xy</code> and <code>no_proxy</code> are commonly lowercase. I don't recall =
any program that only understands them in uppercase, I can't even find one =
that tries them in uppercase. <u><strong>Many programs use the lowercase va=
riant only, including lynx, wget, curl,</strong></u> perl LWP, perl WWW::Se=
arch, python urllib/urllib2, etc. So for these variables, the right form is=
 the lowercase one.</p>
</div>
</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Article sur l'utilisation de docker avec un proxy : <a href=3D"https://b=
log.codeship.com/using-docker-behind-a-proxy/" class=3D"external-link" rel=
=3D"nofollow">https://blog.codeship.com/using-docker-behind-a-proxy/</a></p=
>
    </div>
